cards.lyrics:
The clearing at dawn. COPPERTON stands at a small portable stove, measuring tea leaves with a silver spoon. WIDGET arranges two wooden chairs, adjusting the angle by degrees. A distant explosion rattles the treeline. Neither looks up.

@COPPERTON
(counting under his breath)
One. Two. Three.
(satisfied)
Three and a half.

@WIDGET
The chairs are now at forty-seven degrees from the fire pit. Previously they were at forty-six.

@COPPERTON
Was that uncomfortable?

@WIDGET
It was suboptimal.

@COPPERTON
Then forty-seven it is.

A low rumble from somewhere beyond the trees. A thin column of smoke rises in the distance. WIDGET notes it in a small leather journal.

@WIDGET
Logging: atmospheric disturbance, north-northwest. Probable origin: the Outside.

@COPPERTON
(without turning)
Noted.

@WIDGET
Shall I flag it?

@COPPERTON
Flag it under what category?

@WIDGET
(considering)
"Ambient."

@COPPERTON
That seems appropriate.

The kettle begins to whistle. COPPERTON removes it with great precision and pours two cups, measuring the pour by eye with practiced care.

@COPPERTON
Two minutes forty for the steep. As always.

@WIDGET
You've said two minutes forty for thirty-seven years.

@COPPERTON
And the tea has never once complained.

@WIDGET
(sitting)
No. It hasn't.

They sit. They drink. The smoke on the horizon thickens slightly. They do not mention it.

COPPERTON lifts the biscuit tin from the crate and shakes it once. A single, lonely rattle.

@COPPERTON
Widget.

@WIDGET
(not looking up from journal)
Yes.

@COPPERTON
The tin.

@WIDGET
(still not looking up)
I'm aware.

@COPPERTON
There is one biscuit.

@WIDGET
Yes.

@COPPERTON
One.

@WIDGET
(looks up)
I have counted it, Copperton.

@COPPERTON
(sitting down heavily)
This is a matter of some gravity.

@WIDGET
I've been thinking about rationing.

@COPPERTON
(a long pause)
I beg your pardon.

@WIDGET
We could divide it. Half now. Half tomorrow.

@COPPERTON
(with quiet horror)
Half a biscuit is not a biscuit, Widget. It is a fragment. A ruin.
(beat)
A monument to what once was.

@WIDGET
Or it is half a biscuit.

@COPPERTON
When did you become so brutal?

@WIDGET
I've always been pragmatic. You've chosen to reframe it as brutality.

Long pause. COPPERTON stares at the tin.

@COPPERTON
We could save it.

@WIDGET
For what occasion?

@COPPERTON
A significant occasion.

@WIDGET
(gently)
We may be running low on those.

COPPERTON closes the tin. Sets it down with ceremony. They sit with this.

@COPPERTON
I'll write to the supplier.

@WIDGET
The supplier is in Coventry.

@COPPERTON
Then I'll write a strongly worded letter to Coventry.

@WIDGET
I'll draft it after tea.

@COPPERTON
(quietly)
You're a good friend, Widget.

@WIDGET
I know. I've logged it.

A gust of wind through the clearing. A scorch-marked envelope tumbles end-over-end from the treeline and lands between the two chairs. It is singed at the corners. There is a seal on it that neither robot recognises.

COPPERTON and WIDGET stare at it.

A long pause.

@COPPERTON
Well.

@WIDGET
Yes.

@COPPERTON
It's from outside.

@WIDGET
The postmark is illegible. The damage is consistent with having passed through at least one fire.

@COPPERTON
Should we open it?

@WIDGET
It was addressed to us.

@COPPERTON
How do you know? You haven't touched it.

@WIDGET
It says "occupants of the clearing." We are the occupants of the clearing.

Another pause. COPPERTON retrieves a pair of silver tongs from his waistcoat pocket.

@COPPERTON
I'll use the tongs.

@WIDGET
Of course.

@COPPERTON
One doesn't simply handle correspondence that has been through a fire.

@WIDGET
One doesn't.

COPPERTON lifts the envelope with the tongs. He holds it at arm's length. They both look at it.

@WIDGET
Are you going to open it?

@COPPERTON
I'm considering my options.

@WIDGET
Your options are: open it, or don't open it.

@COPPERTON
(after a beat)
Those are narrow options.

@WIDGET
Most options are, when you look at them closely.

COPPERTON carefully works the flap open with the tongs. He extracts the letter. He holds it out to Widget, still using the tongs.

@WIDGET
(taking it)
I'll read it aloud.

@COPPERTON
That seems right.

WIDGET holds the letter. He reads it once. His eyes move back to the top and he reads it again. COPPERTON waits.

@COPPERTON
Well?

@WIDGET
(reads aloud, very calmly)
"Dear Occupants. The Provisional Reclamation Bureau, acting under authority of the Post-Collapse Resource Management Directive, has identified your location as a site of potential extraction value. A survey team will assess the area within the coming weeks. Residents are advised to make arrangements. Sincerely, The Bureau."

Silence.

@COPPERTON
Resource extraction.

@WIDGET
That's what it says.

@COPPERTON
Of what resource?

@WIDGET
(looks at the forest around them)
I expect... this.

@COPPERTON
The forest.

@WIDGET
And possibly us.

@COPPERTON
Us.

@WIDGET
We are, technically, resources. Our processors. Our power cells. Copperton, we are quite old. The metals in us alone—

@COPPERTON
Widget.

@WIDGET
Yes.

@COPPERTON
Read it again.

WIDGET reads it again. Same calm voice. Same words.

@COPPERTON
(after a moment)
How long?

@WIDGET
It doesn't specify. "Coming weeks."

@COPPERTON
(standing, straightening his waistcoat)
Then we have time.

@WIDGET
For what?

@COPPERTON
(a pause — he doesn't know yet)
Tea.

WIDGET looks at him. Then nods.

@WIDGET
Yes. Tea first.

COPPERTON paces. WIDGET sits at a small camp table with paper, a pen, and the letter.

@COPPERTON
A letter.

@WIDGET
You said that.

@COPPERTON
We write back. Formally. In clear, measured terms.

@WIDGET
That is one approach.

@COPPERTON
It is the correct approach. We present our case. The age of the forest. The unique ecology. The moss.

@WIDGET
The moss.

@COPPERTON
The moss on the north face is seventeen years old, Widget. Seventeen. That doesn't simply—
(gestures broadly)
—replicate itself.

@WIDGET
(writing)
"We write to respectfully dispute—"

@COPPERTON
"Strongly respectfully."

@WIDGET
(pause)
Those words don't go together.

@COPPERTON
They do now. We're inventing a new register. Post-apocalyptic politeness.

@WIDGET
(writing)
"We write to strongly, respectfully dispute the characterisation of this site as a resource to be extracted—"

@COPPERTON
Good. Strong. Firm. But not aggressive.

@WIDGET
Firmly non-aggressive.

@COPPERTON
Precisely.

WIDGET writes. COPPERTON peers over his shoulder.

@COPPERTON
Underline "thirty-seven years."

@WIDGET
It's not in there yet.

@COPPERTON
Put it in and then underline it.

WIDGET writes. A beat.

@WIDGET
I've used the word "moreover" four times.

@COPPERTON
Is that too many?

@WIDGET
For most letters, yes. For this one—
(reads it back)
—no. It sounds exactly right.

@COPPERTON
(nodding slowly)
We are very good at letters.

@WIDGET
We are. It's possible this is our real gift.

@COPPERTON
The tea. The letters. And the chairs.

@WIDGET
Three pillars of civilisation.

@COPPERTON
(satisfied)
Quite.

A rustling from the undergrowth. Both robots turn.

SOOT emerges — a child of about ten, wild-haired, wearing a coat that was once someone else's. She stops at the edge of the clearing. She and the robots look at each other.

A long pause.

@COPPERTON
Hello.

@SOOT
(wary)
You're robots.

@COPPERTON
We are. And you are a child.

@SOOT
I know what I am.

@WIDGET
(pleasantly)
Would you like some tea?

@SOOT
What's tea?

COPPERTON and WIDGET look at each other.

@WIDGET
(carefully)
It's... a hot drink. Made from leaves.

@SOOT
Why?

@COPPERTON
Because it's civilised.

@SOOT
What's civilised?

Another look between the robots.

@COPPERTON
(to Widget, quietly)
This is worse than I thought.

@WIDGET
(to Copperton, quietly)
Don't say that in front of her.

@COPPERTON
(to Soot, warmly)
It means... taking care with things. Taking time. Doing them properly.

@SOOT
(considers this)
Okay.

She walks forward and sits on the ground near the fire. WIDGET pours a third cup.

@WIDGET
Do you take sugar?

@SOOT
What's sugar?

@COPPERTON
(sitting down, adjusting his waistcoat)
This is going to be a long conversation.

@WIDGET
(handing her the cup)
Yes. But I think that's all right.

SOOT holds the cup in both hands. She sniffs it.

@SOOT
It smells like outside. But... nice.

@WIDGET
Yes. That's rather what it's for.

SOOT has finished her tea. She's examining everything — the chairs, the crate, the tin (empty now). COPPERTON and WIDGET watch with the polite attention of hosts uncertain how to proceed.

@WIDGET
You're from the Outside.

@SOOT
Everyone's from the Outside.

@COPPERTON
We're not.

@SOOT
(looks around)
You live here? Just... here?

@WIDGET
For thirty-seven years.

@SOOT
(genuinely baffled)
But what do you do?

@COPPERTON
We have tea. We read. We maintain the clearing.

@SOOT
That's it?

@WIDGET
We also correspond.

@SOOT
With who?

@COPPERTON
(a beat)
Largely with suppliers. And now with the Bureau.

@SOOT
(nodding, like she knows)
The Bureau. They came through our camp last year.

@COPPERTON
What happened?

@SOOT
(matter-of-fact)
They took stuff. Then they left.

@WIDGET
And your camp?

@SOOT
(shrugs)
Gone now.

A beat. The robots absorb this.

@COPPERTON
I see.

@SOOT
It's like that everywhere. Outside. Things just — go. And then you find somewhere else.
(looks at the forest)
I've never seen trees like this. Not all in one place. Not quiet like this.

@WIDGET
It's been quiet for thirty-seven years.

@SOOT
(very quietly)
It's the nicest place I've ever been.

COPPERTON and WIDGET look at each other. Something shifts.

@COPPERTON
(carefully)
You're welcome to stay. For a while.

@SOOT
(looking at the tin)
Do you have more biscuits?

@COPPERTON
(pained)
No.

@SOOT
I know where some are.

@WIDGET
(sitting forward)
I beg your pardon?

Two SURVEYORS in orange high-visibility vests push through the treeline. They carry clipboards, measuring equipment, and the general air of people who have never encountered anything they couldn't quantify.

They stop when they see the robots.

@SURVEYOR 1
(to Surveyor 2)
There are... people here.

@SURVEYOR 2
Are those — robots?

@COPPERTON
(pleasantly)
Good morning. You must be the survey team. We've been expecting you.

@SURVEYOR 1
(checking clipboard)
This site is listed as uninhabited.

@WIDGET
We've been here for thirty-seven years.

@SURVEYOR 2
Robots don't count as habitation.

@COPPERTON
(after a pause)
I see. Would you like some tea?

@SURVEYOR 1
We're on the clock.

@COPPERTON
It won't take long. We've become rather efficient at it.

The surveyors exchange a look. They're thrown off. This is not the usual procedure.

@SURVEYOR 2
(quietly to Surveyor 1)
We could take five minutes.

@SURVEYOR 1
(reluctant)
Fine. Five minutes.

WIDGET is already pouring. The surveyors sit — awkwardly, on the forest floor, since the only chairs are occupied by the robots.

@WIDGET
I'm afraid we only have two chairs.

@SURVEYOR 1
It's fine.

@WIDGET
It isn't, really. But it's the best we can offer under the circumstances.

@SURVEYOR 2
(looking around, genuinely)
It's... nice here.

@COPPERTON
Yes. It is.

An uncomfortable beat.

@SURVEYOR 1
(back to business)
We'll need to start the assessment after this.

@COPPERTON
Of course. Shall I show you the moss?

@SURVEYOR 1
The what?

@COPPERTON
The moss. North face of the log. Seventeen years old. Quite unusual for this region.
(a beat)
I thought it might be relevant.

@SURVEYOR 1
(looking at clipboard)
We're assessing for mineral content and—

@COPPERTON
Of course. Still. The moss.

He says it like a closing argument.

The surveyors have their equipment out. They're measuring trees, taking soil samples, making notes. COPPERTON follows them at a polite distance.

@COPPERTON
I wonder if I might make an observation.

@SURVEYOR 1
(measuring)
Sure.

@COPPERTON
You seem like reasonable people.

@SURVEYOR 1
We're just doing our jobs.

@COPPERTON
Of course. And I respect that enormously. What is your job, exactly, if you don't mind my asking?

@SURVEYOR 1
Resource assessment. If this site has extraction value, we flag it for development.

@COPPERTON
And if it doesn't?

@SURVEYOR 2
(looking up)
Then we flag it as low priority.

@COPPERTON
(brightening)
Excellent. Then perhaps we could discuss the ways in which this site is of — extremely low priority.

Meanwhile, WIDGET has intercepted Surveyor 2 and produced a small laminated card from his waistcoat.

@WIDGET
I've prepared some material that may be of use.

@SURVEYOR 2
(reading card)
"What is a Scone: a brief introduction."

@WIDGET
We find that most misunderstandings between parties stem from an insufficient grounding in the fundamentals.

@SURVEYOR 2
This is a card about baked goods.

@WIDGET
It's a card about civilisation. The scone is a useful entry point.

@SURVEYOR 2
(genuinely uncertain)
Should I...

@WIDGET
Keep it. There's no obligation. But the next time you find yourself somewhere cold and difficult, and someone offers you something warm on a plate — you'll know what it is.

The surveyor looks at the card. Looks at Widget.

@SURVEYOR 2
(quietly)
I've never had a scone.

@WIDGET
(gently)
I know. I could tell.

The surveyors are packing up their equipment, making final notes. COPPERTON and WIDGET stand together. It hasn't gone well.

Then SOOT steps out from behind a tree.

@SOOT
I pulled up the stakes.

@SURVEYOR 1
What?

@SOOT
The orange ones. The ones you put in the ground.

She produces a handful of small orange survey stakes.

@SURVEYOR 1
(to Surveyor 2)
She pulled up our markers.

@SOOT
Both sets. And the ones on the east side.

@SURVEYOR 2
Kid, you can't just—

@SOOT
You're going to take the forest.

@SURVEYOR 1
We're doing an assessment.

@SOOT
I've seen what comes after assessments.

A silence. The surveyors look at her. She doesn't blink.

@COPPERTON
(quietly, to Widget)
She's been in the Outside.

@WIDGET
(quietly back)
She knows what comes after.

@SURVEYOR 1
(to Soot)
Look, we're just doing our jobs—

@SOOT
So am I.

She crosses her arms. A ten-year-old in an oversized coat, holding a fistful of stakes. It is somehow entirely convincing.

The surveyors look at each other.

@SURVEYOR 2
(quietly)
We're going to have to re-survey the boundary markers. That's — that's a whole other day of work.

@SURVEYOR 1
(already retreating)
I'll file a supplementary report.

@SURVEYOR 2
(following)
This is very unusual.

They disappear back through the treeline. Silence returns to the clearing.

@COPPERTON
(after a moment)
That was most resourceful.

@SOOT
(dropping the stakes)
I didn't know if it would work.

@WIDGET
Nothing is certain. That is noted.

@COPPERTON
(looking at the treeline)
And yet.

@SOOT
(sitting down)
Is there any tea left?

Morning. COPPERTON opens a new envelope — this one clean, official, unsinged. He reads it. He reads it again. He sets it down.

@WIDGET
(entering with tray)
The kettle's just—
(stops)
Copperton. You look strange.

@COPPERTON
I believe I feel strange.

@WIDGET
Good strange or bad strange?

@COPPERTON
(holds out the letter)
Read it.

WIDGET sets down the tray. Takes the letter. Reads.

@WIDGET
(very still)
"Following a review of your correspondence dated the fourteenth—"

@COPPERTON
Keep going.

@WIDGET
"—the Bureau has elected to designate the site known as the Forest Clearing, coordinates appended, as a Heritage Site under the Post-Collapse Cultural Preservation Act—"

@COPPERTON
Keep going.

@WIDGET
"—and accordingly removes it from the active extraction schedule indefinitely. The Bureau notes that the correspondence received was, and we quote, 'unusually well-written for a formal dispute, and showed a commendable use of the word moreover.'"

Long pause.

@COPPERTON
They quoted our letter back to us.

@WIDGET
They did.

@COPPERTON
In an official document.

@WIDGET
Yes.

@COPPERTON
(sitting down slowly)
Widget.

@WIDGET
Yes.

@COPPERTON
I think we won.

@WIDGET
I think we did.

A beat. Then another.

@COPPERTON
I expected to feel more triumphant.

@WIDGET
How do you feel?

@COPPERTON
(considering carefully)
Relieved. Quietly. In a way that feels too large to name.

@WIDGET
(sitting down)
Yes. That's exactly it.

They sit with it.

@COPPERTON
Shall we have the good tea?

@WIDGET
We've been saving it for a significant occasion.

@COPPERTON
(looking around at the trees, the moss, the morning)
I think this qualifies.

The clearing. Later. SOOT stands at the small stove, very focused, doing something with the kettle and the tea leaves.

COPPERTON and WIDGET watch from their chairs. Their faces are carefully neutral.

@SOOT
(concentrating)
Is this right?

@COPPERTON
(a beat)
It's... a method.

@SOOT
I watched you do it.

@WIDGET
Yes. You've captured the... spirit of it.

She pours. The tea is the wrong colour. It is poured from too high up. The cup is not warmed first.

She carries both cups over with great care and presents them.

@SOOT
(anxious)
Is it okay?

COPPERTON takes a sip. His expression does not change.

@COPPERTON
It's excellent.

WIDGET takes a sip.

@WIDGET
Very good indeed.

@SOOT
(relieved)
Really?

@COPPERTON
(with complete sincerity)
It's the best tea I've had in recent memory.

@WIDGET
I would say the same.

SOOT sits on the ground between their chairs, satisfied. She pulls her coat around her.

@SOOT
I could learn. Properly. If you wanted to show me.

@COPPERTON
We would like that very much.

@SOOT
I might get it wrong again.

@WIDGET
You'll get it wrong several times. That's how it goes.
(a small pause)
We got it wrong for the first three years.

@SOOT
(surprised)
Really?

@COPPERTON
The steep time. We kept miscounting.

@WIDGET
Thirty-six seconds short, consistently.

@COPPERTON
(quietly)
The tea was fine, though.

@WIDGET
It was always fine.

They sit. The forest around them is still. The kettle is cooling. The tea — whatever it was — is gone.

@SOOT
(almost to herself)
This is a nice place.

@COPPERTON
Yes.

@SOOT
I think I'd like to stay.

@WIDGET
(after a beat)
We think we'd like that too.
